Scipio, the consul now speaking, had with the imperium received from the senate and people os Rome also the jus auspicandi, so that he whom he appointed his deputy had not his own auspicia. We shall find that P. Scipio betook himself afterwards to the province of Spain, which had been committed to him. As consul, he had, wherever he went, authority over all commanders not of consular rank.
